Wives of some Governors joined the various women groups protesting alleged injustice at the gate of the National Assembly on Tuesday. Those who joined were the First Ladies of Ekiti Erelu Bisi Fayemi; Edo, Betty Obaseki and Akwa Ibom, Martha Udom. They were led by Fayemi, who said they were at the protest ground to stand in solidarity for all Nigerian women. “We are here to demand our rights. We want our leaders at the National Assembly to recognise that Nigerian women matter,” she said.   BREAKING: Court sacks Ebonyi Gov, Deputy over defection to…     Buses arrive to evacuate trapped Nigerian students, others…     Commuters stranded as BRT operators withdraw services   Mrs Obaseki also lending support said anyone who neglects the interest of women would lose elections in Edo State. Mrs Emmanuel, who emphasised 35 affirmative actions for women, urged that women be given the opportunity to contribute to the development of society. Chairman of the Nigerians in Diaspora Commission (NIDCOM), Abike Dabiri, was also at the protest. She said women were not asking for the easy way out but only seeking equity. Some female senators also joined in the protest, calling for equality for women.